{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510533","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510533"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:31:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:31:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11587"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11587"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.84,0.07,0.01,0.02,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4214"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76978"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4214","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4214"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11587"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62483"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"1545"},{"type":"tags","id":"4613"},{"type":"tags","id":"4614"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5507"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5526"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76978","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76978"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old woman is brought to the Emergency Department following a witnessed collapse. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she is unconscious and pulseless. Cardiopulmonary resuscitation is in progress and a defibrillator is attached.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe following four rhythm strips are displayed on the defibrillator at the rhythm check in the first four cycles of cardiopulmonary resuscitation, in this order (Images 1, 2, 3, 4). There are no signs of return of spontaneous circulation at any point.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate sequence of defibrillation for these four rhythm checks?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Shock, no shock, shock, no shock","Shock, no shock, shock, shock","No shock, shock, no shock, shock","No shock, no shock, shock, shock","Shock, shock, shock, no shock"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents in cardiac arrest requiring immediate resuscitation. The ECG strips show four different cardiac rhythms that require different management approaches according to Advanced Life Support guidelines.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShock, no shock, shock, no shock\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct sequence based on the rhythms shown. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe first strip shows ventricular fibrillation (VF) characterised by chaotic irregular deflections without identifiable complexes - this requires immediate defibrillation. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe second strip shows organised electrical activity without a pulse (PEA) which is non-shockable. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe third strip shows ventricular tachycardia (VT) which is shockable\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe fourth shows asystole which is non-shockable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuring cardiac arrest, rhythm assessment should occur every two minutes during CPR. Shockable rhythms (VF and pulseless VT) require immediate defibrillation, while non-shockable rhythms (PEA and asystole) should continue with high-quality CPR and addressing reversible causes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ventricular fibrillation (VF) and pulseless ventricular tachycardia (VT) are shockable rhythms requiring immediate defibrillation.","Pulseless electrical activity (PEA) and asystole are non-shockable rhythms where defibrillation is not indicated.","Rhythm assessment during cardiac arrest should occur every two minutes during CPR to guide appropriate interventions."],"references":["Grantham H, Narendranathan R. Basic and advanced cardiac life support. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2012;41:386-90. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2012/june/basic-and-advanced-cardiac-life-support","Flowcharts. In: Resus.org.au [online]. 2022 [cited 21 February 2022]. Available at: https://resus.org.au/guidelines/flowcharts-3/#"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62483"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11587"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16817"},{"type":"media","id":"16818"},{"type":"media","id":"16819"},{"type":"media","id":"16820"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16817","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16817"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/bfabd68a-105f-4143-8b97-ad6318d3bb39.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/bfabd68a-105f-4143-8b97-ad6318d3bb39.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":440,"height":105}},{"type":"media","id":"16818","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16818"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0000ad8e-7792-4cb0-8d33-0ca72e199d77.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0000ad8e-7792-4cb0-8d33-0ca72e199d77.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":413,"height":97}},{"type":"media","id":"16819","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16819"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.co